english:
  title: On Calamities and Portents
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King speaks thus: I, lacking in virtue, am entrusted to stand above the people of one nation. Looking upward, I contemplate how the Former King's founding enterprise was not easily accomplished. Looking downward, I consider how the common folk find it difficult merely to endure. Thus I remain vigilant day and night, respectful of Heaven and diligent toward my people. Yet I fear that the voices of those below do not reach those above, and so I have established the Drum of Remonstrance that grievances might be heard. And yet, in my blindness and want of wisdom, since my ascension to the throne, calamities and portents have cascaded upon us. Twice I have issued edicts seeking words of truth. All such words were worthy of action, yet I failed to implement them fully, losing much credibility in the process.

    Recently, mighty winds have uprooted trees, prolonged rains have blighted the crops, mountains have collapsed, and dwellings have been swept away by floods. Never have the baleful forces of heaven visited such terrible suffering as this day. That harmony is broken and calamities summoned—the fault lies truly with me. I grieve and condemn myself, as though sinking into an abyss. My virtue stands diminished—how shall I restore it? The governance of the realm has gone astray—how shall I correct it? How shall my actions accord with Heaven's will? How shall my offerings move the spirits? Have the rites not been fully ordered? Have the standards not been fully refined? Has not the use and disuse of things been fully made proper? Have not petitions been fully heard? Why do the selections of officials become obstructed? Why do lawsuits languish so long unresolved? Why does the conduct of the people remain unseemly? Why are the burdens of tax and corvée not equally distributed? Do the powerful and tyrannical not yet trample the law? Do the cunning and unscrupulous not yet run rampant? Are there no innocent souls tortured by punishment? Are there no laws frequently altered in confusion? Do resentments fester unseen, yet to surface? Do disasters lie hidden in what we have overlooked, yet to be perceived? As these thoughts arise, I am seized with profound dread. What is the origin of these calamities? Where lies the means to dispel them?

    Hear me, all officials great and small, all scattered ministers of the Sixth Rank and above: if any of you wish to speak, then speak freely—from my own shortcomings above to the grievances of the common people below. Do not hesitate to be direct. Do not fear the powerful and exalted. Lay bare your true thoughts. Hold nothing back in your words. I shall consider carefully and adopt what serves good governance. Though some words may prove mistaken, I shall receive them with generous forbearance.

    Alas! It is the loss of virtue that brings calamities forth. Therefore must I examine my faults and reform myself. Since I seek counsel to mend my errors, how could I not listen with an open heart? Let each of you exhaust your loyalty in aiding my rule. Therefore do I issue this edict for your clear understanding.
  footnotes:
    - The Drum of Remonstrance (申聞鼓) was an instrument placed at court to receive complaints and petitions from the common people.
    - This edict reflects the Confucian doctrine that natural calamities are Heaven's response to moral failings in governance.
    - The address to ministers 'great and small' and those 'of the Sixth Rank and above' reflects the hierarchical structure of Korean court administration.
